## Keeping READMEs in Sync

**CRITICAL**: Always update relevant README files when making changes to the codebase.

### When Adding/Removing Templates
- Update the main `README.md` template table
- Create/update the template's parent `README.md` (e.g., `templates/template-name/README.md`)
- Ensure the template description matches what the code actually does

### When Adding/Removing Recipes
- Update `recipes/README.md` recipe table
- Update the main `README.md` recipe table
- Create/update the recipe's `README.md` (e.g., `recipes/recipe-name/README.md`)
- Ensure the recipe description matches what the code actually does

### When Modifying Template Code
- Update the template's parent `README.md` if features or capabilities change
- Update the description if the template's purpose has changed
- Update the Features section if new functionality is added

### When Modifying Recipe Code
- Update the recipe's `README.md` if the recipe's behavior or purpose changes
- Update the description if what the recipe does has changed
- Update Related SDK Methods if new SDK methods are used
- Update file names in the README if code files are renamed

### When Renaming Files or Folders
- Update all README files that reference the old name
- Check both parent READMEs and individual template/recipe READMEs
- Update file links in READMEs to match new file names

### Checklist Before Completing Changes
- [ ] Main `README.md` template/recipe tables are up to date
- [ ] Template/recipe parent `README.md` exists and is accurate
- [ ] File names in READMEs match actual file names
- [ ] Descriptions accurately reflect what the code does
- [ ] Features/capabilities listed match the implementation
- [ ] SDK method links are correct and complete
